        </span><span class="comment-date">Dec 4, 2012. 7:50 AM<a id="replytolink_C49DMK9HA4MGRBH" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="C49DMK9HA4MGRBH">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">for sure!</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_C49DMK9HA4MGRBH" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CBA009UH9T4F6S3"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix toplevel " style="margin-left:0px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/arduinolover/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/arduinolover/">arduinolover</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Nov 22, 2012. 10:08 AM<a id="replytolink_CBA009UH9T4F6S3" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CBA009UH9T4F6S3">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">Great work, one question, if I manage to put every component in order, is there any piece of code to apply a simple effect (anything) on the incoming audio? I am realy newbie here, thanks a lot keep up the good work! </div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CBA009UH9T4F6S3" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CTDCL25H9T4B690"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  highlight" style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpicstats"><a class="memberstats id-amandaghassaei" href="/member/amandaghassaei/"><img src="/files/deriv/FBC/NVBB/HC3PTPRY/FBCNVBBHC3PTPRY.TINY.jpg" alt="" /><div class="count">53</div></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/amandaghassaei/">amandaghassaei</a> (author) says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Nov 24, 2012. 4:58 AM<a id="replytolink_CTDCL25H9T4B690" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CTDCL25H9T4B690">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">Thanks!  Are you going to output the audio?  Something simple would be to multiply all the incoming data by 2 to amplify the signal.  If you wanted to change the shape of the signal you could try squaring the data before outputting it.  You could DC offset it by adding a value to it, or subtract the incoming data from 255 to invert the signal.  Does that make sense?  If you are looking for some more interesting effects you should check out my vocal effects box project: <br>http://instructables.com/id/Arduino-Vocal-Effects-Box/</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CTDCL25H9T4B690" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CHK4RYQH8CVHY76"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix toplevel " style="margin-left:0px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/Panichou/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/Panichou/">Panichou</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 17, 2012. 12:37 PM<a id="replytolink_CHK4RYQH8CVHY76" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CHK4RYQH8CVHY76">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">Hi ! I am working on a project on digital amplification ( for academic purpose ). <br>I want to amplify a simple signal like an A ( not quite sure, I am french and we call it a &quot; La &quot;, frequence = 55hz ) <br>It won't be much about audio at first, just trying to figure out how arduino works right know ! <br> <br>Here's my first attempt : <br> <br> // Multiply a pure sine from a function generator by 2 <br> <br>int incoming;                                      // define &quot;incoming&quot; as a variable  <br>#define DIGIO 13                              // digital output at pin 13 <br>void setup() <br>{ <br>pinmode(DIGIO, OUTPUT};            //set pin 13 as an output <br>void loop(){  <br>  incoming = analogRead(A0);      //read input from A0 <br>  incoming = 2*incoming;               //multiply A0 input by 2 <br>  DIGIO = incoming;                        // send result to pin 13 <br>} <br> <br>I'll put a function generator in A0. It is my first program ever so it is a little fuzy. I am just not quite sure for how to return the final value, is DIGIO = incoming the right way to do it ?  </div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CHK4RYQH8CVHY76" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="C4PDUVPH8CVHY9B"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  " style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/Panichou/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/Panichou/">Panichou</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 17, 2012. 12:51 PM<a id="replytolink_C4PDUVPH8CVHY9B" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="C4PDUVPH8CVHY9B">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">* correction :  <br>void setup() {  <br>pinmode(DIGIO, OUTPUT); // set pin 13 as output <br>} </div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_C4PDUVPH8CVHY9B" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CKYG729H8CVGCBG"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  highlight" style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpicstats"><a class="memberstats id-amandaghassaei" href="/member/amandaghassaei/"><img src="/files/deriv/FBC/NVBB/HC3PTPRY/FBCNVBBHC3PTPRY.TINY.jpg" alt="" /><div class="count">53</div></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/amandaghassaei/">amandaghassaei</a> (author) says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 17, 2012. 2:57 PM<a id="replytolink_CKYG729H8CVGCBG" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CKYG729H8CVGCBG">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">you're almost there, pin 13 is a digital output, it can only output 5V ( digitalWrite(13,HIGH) ) or ground ( digitalWrite(13,LOW) ).&nbsp; Unfortunately, the Arduino does not have any analog outputs, but using digital pins 0-7 you can make a simple 8 bit DAC.&nbsp; Look at what I set up <a href="http://www.instructables.com/id/Arduino-Audio-Output/" rel="nofollow">here</a><br> You can send this dac a number between 0 and 255 to get it to output a voltage between 0 and 5V using the command:<br> <br> <strong>PORTD = number;</strong><br> <br> one more thing you have to think about is that the values you get from analogRead(A0) are between 0 and 1023, when you multiply this by two, then you get values between 0 and 2046, but the dac will only output values between 0 and 255.&nbsp; If you want to keep the line:<br> <br> <strong>incoming = 2*incoming;</strong><br> <br> then you will need to restrict your analog in values to number between 0 and 127 (between 0 and 0.625V)<br> <br> one way you can do this is by dc offsetting your incoming mic signal by 1/2*0.625 = 0.3125V instead of 2.5V as I recommended in this instructable.&nbsp; And then being careful not to let the amplitude of the signal go above 0.3125V<br> <br> Another (and I think better way) is to keep the signal biased around 2.5V with an amplitude of 0.3125.&nbsp; This will give you values between 2.5-0.3125V = 2.1875V and 2.5+0.3125 = 2.8125V.&nbsp; When you use analogRead(A0) the arduino will read the signal as a value in this range:<br> <br> <strong>min = 2.1875V/5V*1023 = 448<br> max = 2.8125V/5V*1023 = 575</strong><br> <br> you can then subtract 448 from these values so you get values within this range:<br> <br> <strong>min = 448-448 = 0<br> max = 575-448 = 127</strong><br> <br> then you can multiply them by 2 and get numbers between 0 and 255 which can be sent straight to the 8 bit dac.<br> <br> I think this way is better bc if you want to do other things with the audio input later, you can simply amplify the signal more and use the full 0-1023 range to read with A0.&nbsp; by DC offsetting around 0.3125, the Arduino will start clipping the bottom part of your wave as soon as the amplitude of the signal goes above 0.3125V.<br> <br> let me know how this sounds, does it make sense?<br> <br> </div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CKYG729H8CVGCBG" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="C15TKJ8H994BWUS"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  " style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/Panichou/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/Panichou/">Panichou</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Nov 9, 2012. 1:51 PM<a id="replytolink_C15TKJ8H994BWUS" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="C15TKJ8H994BWUS">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">One more question. <br>Why don't you use the map function ( map(analogRead(A0),0,1023,0,127)) instead of a manual substraction ?  <br>Is it the same thing at the end ?</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_C15TKJ8H994BWUS" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CWFLZN4H994X8ZL"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  highlight" style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpicstats"><a class="memberstats id-amandaghassaei" href="/member/amandaghassaei/"><img src="/files/deriv/FBC/NVBB/HC3PTPRY/FBCNVBBHC3PTPRY.TINY.jpg" alt="" /><div class="count">53</div></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/amandaghassaei/">amandaghassaei</a> (author) says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Nov 9, 2012. 4:58 PM<a id="replytolink_CWFLZN4H994X8ZL" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CWFLZN4H994X8ZL">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">generally with this high frequency interrupt stuff, I like to avoid using any of the commands from the Arduino library, because they usually use more lines of code than are absolutely necessary (so that they are generalized for lots of possible inputs).</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CWFLZN4H994X8ZL" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CKYW18LH8TTNQC8"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  " style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/Panichou/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/Panichou/">Panichou</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 28, 2012. 6:42 AM<a id="replytolink_CKYW18LH8TTNQC8" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CKYW18LH8TTNQC8">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">Hi ! <br>I do not understand the difference between <br> &quot; PORTD = 3 ;&quot; and &quot; digitalwrite( 3 , HIGH ); &quot; <br></div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CKYW18LH8TTNQC8" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CEBYNPDH8RK8OCI"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  highlight" style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpicstats"><a class="memberstats id-amandaghassaei" href="/member/amandaghassaei/"><img src="/files/deriv/FBC/NVBB/HC3PTPRY/FBCNVBBHC3PTPRY.TINY.jpg" alt="" /><div class="count">53</div></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/amandaghassaei/">amandaghassaei</a> (author) says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 28, 2012. 12:44 PM<a id="replytolink_CEBYNPDH8RK8OCI" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="CEBYNPDH8RK8OCI">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">digitalWrite(3,HIGH) turns pin 3 to HIGH and leaves the other outputs alone <br> <br>PORTD = 3 turns pis 0 and 1 to HIGH and pins 2-7 to LOW.  because 3 in binary is 00000011.  These eight digits represent each of the 8 pins in port D (pins 0-7).  The first 6 digits are 0's, so pins 7-2 are LOW, the last two digits are 1's, so pins 1 and 0 are HIGH. <br> <br>more info here: <br>http://www.arduino.cc/en/Reference/PortManipulation</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_CEBYNPDH8RK8OCI" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="COZ77RTH8FOFWEV"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  " style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/Panichou/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/Panichou/">Panichou</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 20, 2012. 4:06 PM<a id="replytolink_COZ77RTH8FOFWEV" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="COZ77RTH8FOFWEV">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">This is awesome thank you ! Really learned something here. <br>I get the idea of the biased signal but I do not quit understand why do yo substract 448 ( how does the arduino read a 2,18V as a digital 0 ? )</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_COZ77RTH8FOFWEV" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="C5WKC9NH8FYP5F0"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  highlight" style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpicstats"><a class="memberstats id-amandaghassaei" href="/member/amandaghassaei/"><img src="/files/deriv/FBC/NVBB/HC3PTPRY/FBCNVBBHC3PTPRY.TINY.jpg" alt="" /><div class="count">53</div></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/amandaghassaei/">amandaghassaei</a> (author) says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 22, 2012. 10:10 AM<a id="replytolink_C5WKC9NH8FYP5F0" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="C5WKC9NH8FYP5F0">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">good question, the arduino reads 2.18V as a 448 through its analog input because of the following relationship: <br> <br>2.1875V / 5V *1023 = 448 <br> <br>(remember the arduino reads 5V as 1023 and 0V as 0, so any voltage in between (like 2.18) will give you a value between 1023 and 0) <br> <br>but, since the wave we're looking at only has a voltage between 2.18 and 2.81, we can subtract 448 from all incoming measurements of the wave so that values of 2.18V get stored in the arduino's memory at &quot;0&quot;.  the command would be like this: <br> <br>incoming = analogRead(A0) - 448; <br> <br>This way when we multiply all the values by 2 they fit nicely within the 0-255 range we want.  hopefully that helps?</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_C5WKC9NH8FYP5F0" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="C77K0V5H8TTNQCA"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  " style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpic"><a href="/member/Panichou/"><img src="/static/defaultIMG/user.TINY.gif" alt="" /></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/Panichou/">Panichou</a> says:
        </span><span class="comment-date">Oct 28, 2012. 6:43 AM<a id="replytolink_C77K0V5H8TTNQCA" class="btn btn-mini reply-comment login-required" href="C77K0V5H8TTNQCA">Reply</a></span></div><div class="txt comment-txt">Okay I Got It !  <br>Here it is :  <br> <br> <br>int incoming;                   // define &quot;incoming&quot; as a variable  <br>void setup(){ <br>  for (byte i=0;i&lt;8;i++){pinMode(i,OUTPUT);//set digital pins 0-7 <br>  } <br>} <br>void loop(){  <br>  incoming = analogRead(A0)-448;    //read input from A0 <br>  incoming = 2*incoming;        //multiply A0 input by 2 <br>  PORTD = incoming;             // send result to pins 0-7 <br>}</div><div id="files" class=""><a name="files"></a></div><div id="commentactioncontainer_C77K0V5H8TTNQCA" class="comment-actions"><div class="fr mt5"></div></div></div><a name="CJS5XEZH8RK8OF1"></a><div class="comment-entry clearfix  highlight" style="margin-left:52px;"><div class="comment-authorpicstats"><a class="memberstats id-amandaghassaei" href="/member/amandaghassaei/"><img src="/files/deriv/FBC/NVBB/HC3PTPRY/FBCNVBBHC3PTPRY.TINY.jpg" alt="" /><div class="count">53</div></a></div><div class="comment-info"><span class="comment-author"><a class="author-link " href="/member/amandaghassaei/">amandaghassaei</a> (author) says:
